&gt; I tend to prefer to add a test case with no tests (you get an 
&gt; Assert: no
&gt; tests found in testcase: xxx)  or add a test method which fails with a
&gt; message &quot;Not implemented!&quot;.
&gt; 
&gt; This way at least I&#39;m reminded every time I run the test 
&gt; suite. I can&#39;t do
&gt; paper lists as I usually lose or damage them  somehow, and my 
&gt; mental list
&gt; can easily become lost ;)
&gt; 
&gt; I do realise though that this means I do have to mentally 
&gt; block out the red
&gt; tests/suites that are just those  not implemented, from those that are
&gt; failing.
&gt; 
&gt; Maybe JUnit could be enhanced to have Amber tests for these 
&gt; situations?
&gt; 
&gt; Green: Test passes
&gt; Amber: Test fails as it isn&#39;t implemented
&gt; Red:   test fails
&gt; 
&gt; What do people think?

I am working exactly in the same way :)

I&#39;d love to see a hint for &quot;not yet implemented&quot; tests.

Bernd


